Benjamin:

I have sent a trial pdf letter to amd64_hacker which I saved as a 1 bit 
pdf.  This 2 page letter only took up 60kb.  If I save it as JPEG, I 
believe the file would be approximately 10 times that size.  I am 
waiting to see if the copy amd64_hacker received seems good enough to 
use.  The resolution may be a little too thin -- at least for the pen I 
used.

The pdf format lets us make a multi-page file if we want to, and it 
really isn&#39;t that much additional trouble.  You make your individual 
scans, then use PDF.995 to combine them into a single file.  So the 
process would be something like this:  a person downloads an existing 
file from the website, scans his letter, saves it as a pdf file.  Uses 
PDF.995 to combine his addition to the existing file and then uploads 
the whole shebang back to the website replacing the original file.

Regarding JPEG:  is there any way that a second writer can append a scan 
of their QS addition to an original JPEG scan?  If not, then we would 
just be uploading a series of disconnected letters (files) to the site 
and it would not be obvious who was responding to what.  Perhaps that 
doesn&#39;t matter, but it would be different from the original concept of a 
letter that makes the rounds and is added to by each new reader.  The 
latter idea would seem to encourage people to participate.  We could 
have uploaded scanned writing seven years ago when I started the 
website, but that has not happened to any great extent.

I can start another site for reading (and the encouragement of writing) 
practice.  That would give us another 100mb of space devoted to that 
purpose if that is the consensus of the people interested in this.


Paige

